ntReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>When describing a perceived event to others, a communicator will tailor the message to the audience. The project examines how a message which is ?tuned? to the audience can change or bias the way in which the original event is remembered and evaluated by the communicator. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The project focuses on how eyewitnesses produce their own memory biases during the process of communication with others. A key factor to be varied is ?shared reality,? which captures how communicators experience the communication with the person they are tuning to (eg, whether they feel they achieve a joint view with their audience). The likelihood of shared reality creation (high vs. low uncertainty about the event; shared-reality vs. instrumental goals for audience tuning; positive vs. negative audience feedback; appropriate vs. inappropriate audience) will be manipulated in a series of studies. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Standard memory measures and source-memory tests will determine whether eyewitnesses exhibiting a greater memory bias are less likely to discriminate correctly between information from the witnessed event and communicated information. The novel insights from this project will be useful from both a basic and an applied perspective, for example, by providing a better understanding&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-04-01</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-04-02</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>39533</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>They are used by other researchers to disseminate information in cases of eyewitness identification error.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2010</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>E6E5C0BA-905C-4F56-96BF-951827E7CDEC</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>54610898a8d421.45467475</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The findings are that communication can impact eyewitness memory as detailed in my impact report (already) to the research council</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>I have detailed this already in the impact report provided to the council</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>12C1CC52-EAC1-4646-93CF-6A74907761CF</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546107ee5408e9.18575454</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.pc.rhul.ac.uk/sites/rheg/</gtr:url></gtr:keyFin